A few weeks ago, a Digital Executive at a large Swiss corporate asked me if Ginetta could also support on their Digital Business Strategy. I said “It depends. If you are looking for a 300-page strategy paper, then probably not. However, if you are looking to create a Digital Business Strategy that is truly customer-centered, then maybe yes”.

My point was that we are not a business consulting firm that creates 5-year transformation programs, with the hope that change will come out at the other end of the tunnel. We are a Digital Experience Company. And part of that is Strategy too. However, everything we do needs to have a clear purpose with the human in the center.

So often, companies approach change management top down. They hire consultants to map out change programs and transformation initiatives. And they often look very good on paper. However, they are also often hard to put into practice because they are detached from the human.

Making change is hard. People, by design, don’t want to change. Sure, some do. But most don’t.

However, change is almost impossible if you don’t put the human in the center.

Why is that?

Because change is not a process. It’s a human experience.

And as such, it needs to be treated with the same care and attention as any other human experience.

But how do you put the human in the center of change?

Here are three ways to do just that:

1. Start with the end in mind

When you start a change initiative, it’s easy to get caught up in the details. You want to know exactly how you’re going to get from point A to point B. But before you do that, you need to know what point B looks like.

What is the end goal of your change initiative? What does success look like? And most importantly, how will it impact the human?

When you start with the end in mind, you can create a clear vision for your change initiative. And that vision will help guide you and your team through the process.

2. Make it personal

Change is hard because it’s personal. It’s a threat to our sense of self and our sense of control.

That’s why it’s so important to make change personal. To help people see how it will benefit them.

When you make change personal, you create a sense of ownership. And that ownership is what will drive people to make the change.

3. Create a safe space

Change is scary. It’s uncertain. And that uncertainty can be paralyzing.

That’s why it’s so important to create a safe space for change. A space where people feel comfortable sharing their fears and their concerns.

When you create a safe space, you give people the freedom to explore and to experiment. And that freedom is what will allow them to embrace change.

So, the next time you’re thinking about making a change, remember to put the human in the center. Because change is not a process. It’s a human experience.

And as such, it needs to be treated with the same care and attention as any other human experience.

This package allows you to authenticate guest users for Firebase using Laravel.


Installation
------------

You can install the package via composer:

```bash
composer require jenssegers/laravel-firebase
```


Configuration
-------------

After installing the package, you need to add the service provider to the `providers` array in `config/app.php`:

```php
'providers' => [
    // ...
    Jenssegers\Firebase\FirebaseServiceProvider::class,
],
```


Next, you need to add the following alias to the `aliases` array in `config/app.php`:

```php
'aliases' => [
    // ...
    'Firebase' => Jenssegers\Firebase\Facades\Firebase::class,
],
```


Finally, you need to publish the configuration file with:

```bash
php artisan vendor:publish --provider="Jenssegers\Firebase\FirebaseServiceProvider" --tag="config"
```


Usage
-----

You can use the `Firebase` facade to authenticate guest users for Firebase:

```php
use Firebase;

$firebase = Firebase::forge();

$user = $firebase->createUser([
    'uid' => 'some-uid',
    'displayName' => 'John Doe',
    'photoUrl' => 'http://www.example.com/john-doe.jpg',
    'email' => 'john.doe@example.com',
    'emailVerified' => false,
    'phoneNumber' => '+1 123 456 7890',
    'password' => 'secret-password',
    'disabled' => false,
]);

// The user object
$user = $firebase->getAuth()->getUserByUid('some-uid');

// The user token
$token = $firebase->getAuth()->createCustomToken('some-uid');
```


Testing
-------

``` bash
$ composer test
```
